The SPC Pacific Data Hub tracks sea level measurements across `{r} n_nations` Pacific Island nations and territories dating back to `{r} year_min`. One finding stands out: Papua New Guinea sits at the top of every ranked chart in this dataset. Its sea levels are rising at **`{r} png_slope` mm per year** — faster than any other Pacific nation on record. This report examines that finding: what the data shows, how PNG compares across the Pacific, and what it means alongside warming temperatures and growing disaster costs.


## PNG leads a ranking no nation wants to top

<span class="section-label">The key finding</span>

A linear trend model fitted to each country's `{r} year_max - year_min`-year record places PNG at the head of the table. The estimate of `{r} png_slope` mm/yr (95% CI: `{r} png_ci_low`–`{r} png_ci_high` mm/yr) is statistically significant and sits clear of the next-fastest nations.

```{r}
#| label: ranked-trends-plot
#| fig-height: 6.5

ggplot(trend_ci,
       aes(x = slope * 1000,
           y = reorder(country, slope),
           color = subregion)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed",
             color = "#cc0000", linewidth = 0.5) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(xmin = conf.low * 1000, xmax = conf.high * 1000),
                width = 0.4, linewidth = 0.5, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = country == "Papua New Guinea"),
             size = 3) +
  scale_color_manual(values = subregion_colours) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(`FALSE` = 16, `TRUE` = 18),
                     guide = "none") +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.05, 0.06))) +
  labs(
    title    = "Rate of sea level rise per country (1993–2023)",
    x = "Trend (mm per year)", y = NULL, color = "Subregion",
    caption  = "Fig 1: Sea level rise per country in the Pacific"
  ) +
  theme_essay() +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(0.82, 0.15),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    plot.background = element_blank()
  )
```


Every confidence interval in this chart lies entirely above zero. No country shows a flat or declining trend — the rise is universal. But PNG's rate is the highest, and it matters: a nation rising at `{r} png_slope` mm/yr faces a meaningfully different trajectory from one rising at 3.2 mm/yr (Tokelau, at the bottom of this chart).

::: {.pull-quote}
PNG has `{r} round((png_slope / min(trend_ci$slope * 1000)) * 100 - 100, 0)`% faster sea level rise than the slowest Pacific nation in this dataset. With roughly 9 million people and thousands of kilometres of coastline, that differential has direct implications for coastal infrastructure, agriculture, and communities.
:::


## PNG is not alone — but it leads

<span class="section-label">The Pacific-wide picture</span>

PNG's position at the top does not mean the rest of the Pacific is safe. All `{r} n_nations` nations show the same upward direction over the full period. The chart below shows every country's trajectory, with PNG highlighted.

```{r}
#| label: spaghetti-trends-smooth
#| fig-height: 5

df_spag <- sea_level_clean |>
  mutate(
    is_png = country == "Papua New Guinea",
    highlight = if_else(is_png, "Papua New Guinea", "Other nations")
  )

# Generate smooth predictions per country using loess
df_smooth <- df_spag |>
  group_by(country, is_png, highlight) |>
  do({
    mod <- loess(sea_level_anomaly_m ~ year, data = ., span = 0.4)
    data.frame(
      year = seq(1993, 2023, length.out = 50),
      smooth = predict(mod, newdata = data.frame(year = seq(1993, 2023, length.out = 50)))
    )
  }) |>
  ungroup()

#Defining point_data
point_data <- df_spag |>
  mutate(
    point_color = if_else(is_png, col_ocean, "#d5e8f3"),
    point_size = if_else(is_png, 3.5, 0.5),
    point_alpha = if_else(is_png, 1.0, 0.2)
  )

# Define colours for smoothed lines: PNG in bold , others in very faint grey
highlight_colours <- c(
  "Papua New Guinea" = col_ocean,
  "Other nations" = "#c5d5e0"
)

ggplot() +
  # PNG smoothed line - THICK and BOLD
  geom_line(
    data = df_smooth |> filter(is_png),
    aes(x = year, y = smooth, colour = highlight),
    linewidth = 1.8, alpha = 1.0
  ) +
  # Other nations smoothed lines - THIN and FAINT
  geom_line(
    data = df_smooth |> filter(!is_png),
    aes(x = year, y = smooth, group = country, colour = highlight),
    linewidth = 0.3, alpha = 0.35
  ) +
  # PNG data points - LARGE and SOLID
  geom_point(
    data = point_data |> filter(is_png),
    aes(x = year, y = sea_level_anomaly_m),
    color = col_ocean, size = 3.5, alpha = 1.0
  ) +
  # Other nations data points - TINY and FAINT
