## Subregion comparison

<span class="section-label">Where Melanesia stands</span>

PNG belongs to Melanesia, which as a subregion records the highest mean rate of rise. The table below compares all three subregions.

```{r}
#| label: subregion-rate-table
subregion_trend <- sea_level_sub |>
  nest_by(subregion) |>
  mutate(model = list(lm(sea_level_anomaly_m ~ year, data = data))) |>
  reframe(tidy(model, conf.int = TRUE)) |>
  filter(term == "year") |>
  select(subregion, slope = estimate, conf.low, conf.high)

subregion_trend |>
  mutate(
    rate = round(slope * 1000, 2),
    ci   = paste0(round(conf.low * 1000, 2), " – ",
                  round(conf.high * 1000, 2), " mm/yr")
  ) |>
  select(Subregion = subregion,
         `Rise rate (mm/yr)` = rate,
         `95% confidence interval` = ci) |>
  gt() |>
  tab_header(
    title    = md("**Sea level rise by subregion**"),
    subtitle = "All rates statistically significant at p < 0.001"
  ) |>
  tab_style(
    style = list(cell_text(weight = "bold", color = "#0a2342"),
                 cell_fill(color = "#eaf4fb")),
    locations = cells_column_labels()
  ) |>
  tab_style(
    style = cell_fill(color = "#f0fbf8"),
    locations = cells_body(rows = Subregion == "Melanesia")
  ) |>
  cols_align(align = "center", columns = 2:3) |>
  tab_options(table.width = pct(70), table.align = "left")
```

Melanesia's rate is marginally higher than Micronesia and Polynesia, but the confidence intervals overlap considerably. PNG's rate exceeds its own subregion's average — it is not simply carrying Melanesia up; it genuinely stands apart within the region.

