## Not even El Niño is holding the rise back

<span class="section-label">The ENSO signal</span>

A reasonable question when examining PNG's sea level record is whether natural climate variability — particularly the El Niño–Southern Oscillation — could explain the trend or offer any relief. The short answer is: less and less.

During El Niño events, warm water migrates eastward and sea levels across the western Pacific tend to fall temporarily. PNG, sitting in the western warm pool, should be among the most affected by this suppression. But the data tells a more complicated story.

```{r}
#| label: dual-axis-enso-plot
#| fig-height: 5

if (!is.null(oni_annual)) {
  pacific_mean <- sea_level_sub |>
    summarise(mean_anomaly = mean(sea_level_anomaly_m), .by = year)

  pacific_oni <- pacific_mean |>
    left_join(oni_annual, by = "year") |>
    filter(!is.na(oni_mean))

  sl_range    <- range(pacific_oni$mean_anomaly)
  oni_range_v <- range(pacific_oni$oni_mean)
  sf          <- diff(sl_range) / diff(oni_range_v)
  offs        <- sl_range[1] - oni_range_v[1] * sf

  el_nino_rects <- tibble(
    label = c("1997–98", "2009–10", "2015–16"),
    xmin  = c(1996.5, 2008.5, 2014.5),
    xmax  = c(1998.5, 2010.5, 2016.5)
  )

  ggplot(pacific_oni, aes(x = year)) +
    geom_rect(data = el_nino_rects,
              aes(xmin = xmin, xmax = xmax, ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf),
              inherit.aes = FALSE,
              fill = col_coral, alpha = 0.08) +
    geom_text(data = el_nino_rects,
              aes(x = (xmin + xmax) / 2,
                  y = max(pacific_oni$mean_anomaly) * 0.96,
                  label = label),
              inherit.aes = FALSE,
              color = "#922b21", size = 2.8, fontface = "bold") +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "#aac4d4",
               linewidth = 0.3, linetype = "dotted") +
    geom_line(aes(y = oni_mean * sf + offs),
              color = col_coral, linewidth = 0.8,
              linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.75) +
    geom_point(aes(y = oni_mean * sf + offs),
               color = col_coral, size = 1.8, alpha = 0.7) +
    geom_line(aes(y = mean_anomaly),
              color = col_ocean, linewidth = 1.2) +
    geom_point(aes(y = mean_anomaly),
               color = col_ocean, size = 2.2) +
    scale_y_continuous(
      name = "Sea level anomaly (m)",
      sec.axis = sec_axis(~ (. - offs) / sf,
                          name = "Oceanic Niño Index (ONI)"),
      expand = expansion(mult = c(0.05, 0.08))
    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1993, 2023, by = 3)) +
    annotate("text", x = 1994, y = max(pacific_oni$mean_anomaly) * 0.80,
             label = "Sea level (m)", color = col_ocean,
             fontface = "bold", hjust = 0, size = 3.0) +
    annotate("text", x = 1994, y = max(pacific_oni$mean_anomaly) * 0.63,
             label = "ONI (dashed)", color = col_coral,
             fontface = "bold", hjust = 0, size = 3.0) +
    labs(
      title   = "El Niño suppresses sea levels — but the trend keeps climbing",
      x = NULL,
      caption = "Fig 4: Sea level (blue) vs ONI(red), showing whether El Niño has suppressed sea levels or not. Note that ONI from NOAA Climate Prediction Center"
    ) +
    theme_essay() +
    theme(
      axis.title.y.left  = element_text(color = col_ocean),
      axis.text.y.left   = element_text(color = col_ocean),
      axis.title.y.right = element_text(color = col_coral),
      axis.text.y.right  = element_text(color = col_coral),
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      plot.background = element_blank()
    )
}
```

::: {.enso-note}
**Comparing 1997–98 and 2015–16 is the key test.** Both El Niño events were of similar strength by ONI measures, yet the 2015–16 dip was noticeably shallower. The most likely explanation: the underlying long-term rise had grown large enough to partially offset the El Niño suppression. As the baseline keeps climbing, temporary dips will become progressively smaller relative to the trend.
:::

Sea level anomalies are also measurably lower during El Niño years on average (Wilcoxon test, p = `{r} round(wilcox_p, 3)`), confirming the suppression effect is real. But it is losing ground to the trend.


```{r}
#| label: oni-sensitivity-plot
#| fig-height: 6

oni_models <- sea_oni |>
  nest_by(country) |>
  mutate(
    mod_trend     = list(lm(sea_level_anomaly_m ~ year, data = data)),
    mod_trend_oni = list(lm(sea_level_anomaly_m ~ year + oni_mean, data = data))
  ) |>
  mutate(
    r2_trend     = summary(mod_trend)$r.squared,
    r2_trend_oni = summary(mod_trend_oni)$r.squared
  )

oni_coefs <- oni_models |>
  reframe(tidy(mod_trend_oni, conf.int = TRUE)) |>
  filter(term == "oni_mean") |>
  select(country, oni_coef = estimate) |>
  left_join(subregion_map, by = "country") |>
  left_join(oni_models |> select(country, r2_trend, r2_trend_oni),
            by = "country") |>
  mutate(r2_gain = r2_trend_oni - r2_trend)

ggplot(oni_coefs,
       aes(x = r2_gain,
           y = reorder(country, r2_gain),
           fill = subregion)) +
  geom_col(alpha = 0.75, width = 0.7) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = subregion_colours) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    labels = label_percent(accuracy = 1),
    expand = expansion(mult = c(0.01, 0.06))
  ) +
  labs(
    title    = "ENSO sensitivity varies dramatically across the Pacific",
    x = "% increase in model R² after adding ENSO (ONI)",
    y = NULL, fill = "Subregion",
    caption  = "Fig 5: This chart shows how much adding ENSO (El Niño and La Niña) improved the sea-level model(linear) for each Pacific Island country. Higher percentages mean that ENSO plays a bigger role in explaining sea-level changes in that country. ONI source: NOAA Climate Prediction Center"
  ) +
  theme_essay() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    plot.background = element_blank()
  )
```

<p class="chart-note">PNG lies near the middle of the ranking. Adding ENSO improves the linear model, but the long-term sea-level rise remains the dominant signal. Western Micronesia (Palau, Guam, FSM) shows the strongest ENSO influence (40–50% improvement), whereas most Polynesian countries show little additional improvement (<5%).</p>

