## Summary of findings

<span class="section-label">Key findings</span>

This analysis draws on `{r} nrow(sea_level_clean)` annual observations from `{r} n_nations` Pacific Island nations spanning `{r} year_min`–`{r} year_max`, across four official SPC datasets.

::: {.finding-card}
**PNG has the highest rate of sea level rise in the dataset.** At `{r} png_slope` mm/yr (95% CI: `{r} png_ci_low`–`{r} png_ci_high` mm/yr), PNG leads all 21 nations. The confidence interval lies entirely above zero.
:::

::: {.finding-card}
**The rise is universal across the Pacific.** All 21 nations show statistically significant positive trends. PNG is fastest, but no country is exempt.
:::

::: {.finding-card}
**Melanesia has the highest subregional mean rate**, though confidence intervals across all three subregions overlap substantially. PNG's rate exceeds even Melanesia's average.
:::

::: {.finding-card}
**El Niño events suppress sea levels but cannot reverse the trend.** Sea levels are measurably lower in El Niño years (Wilcoxon p = `{r} round(wilcox_p, 3)`). However, the 2015–16 dip was shallower than 1997–98 despite comparable El Niño strength — consistent with the long-term rise progressively offsetting the suppression.
:::

::: {.finding-card}
**PNG's ENSO sensitivity is moderate.** Adding ONI to the trend model explains some additional variance in PNG, but far less than in western Micronesia (40–50%). The trend, not ENSO, dominates PNG's sea level record.
:::

::: {.finding-card}
**Surface and sea surface temperatures are also trending upward** across all subregions, adding pressure on coral reefs and fisheries alongside the sea level signal.
:::

::: {.finding-card}
**Cumulative disaster losses reach $`{r} total_loss_bn`B USD**, with `{r} total_persons_m`M people directly affected across Pacific nations — the real-world cost of the trends above.
:::

::: {.pull-quote}
Across every dataset examined here, Papua New Guinea's position is consistent: highest rate, Melanesia's largest nation, and among the Pacific's most exposed coastlines. The trajectory is clear. What happens next depends on decisions being made far from PNG's shores.
:::

